00:25:01.176 --> 00:25:06.873
thought maybe,
to bring the discussion down

00:25:06.873 --> 00:25:11.730
from the clouds here,
I would ask Jim:

00:25:11.730 --> 00:25:17.147
Is the ghost of Adam Smith
alive in the boardroom in

00:25:17.147 --> 00:25:19.380
corporate America?
 

00:25:19.380 --> 00:25:24.906
Jim Alexander:
 Well, the self-image of

00:25:24.906 --> 00:25:27.608
Adam Smith is alive.
 

00:25:27.608 --> 00:25:31.940
The ideology that would be
espoused is that of Adam Smith.

00:25:31.940 --> 00:25:36.936
The substance is not there,
I believe, but most of the

00:25:36.936 --> 00:25:42.406
people would pass the polygraph
test that they believe it's

00:25:42.406 --> 00:25:43.349
there.
 

00:25:43.349 --> 00:25:45.230
Prof: Okay, that's good.
 

00:25:45.230 --> 00:25:48.670
Now let's--here's an
interesting exercise.

00:25:48.670 --> 00:25:51.730
There are about a dozen MBAs in
the group here.

00:25:51.730 --> 00:26:01.890
Every MBA--every MBA period,
has learned the Porter Forces.

00:26:01.890 --> 00:26:05.710
What are the Porter Forces?
 

00:26:05.710 --> 00:26:09.943
The Porter Forces are the rules
of thumb you need to make above

00:26:09.943 --> 00:26:12.130
average profits within a firm.
 

00:26:12.130 --> 00:26:15.075
One of them is:
You don't want too much

00:26:15.075 --> 00:26:17.710
competition--direct competition.
 

00:26:17.710 --> 00:26:20.250
Direct competition erodes
profits.

00:26:20.250 --> 00:26:23.519
You want high barriers to entry.
 

00:26:23.519 --> 00:26:28.611
You don't want powerful buyers
who can drive down your price

00:26:28.611 --> 00:26:30.509
through negotiating.
 

00:26:30.509 --> 00:26:33.340
For example,
tire companies face very

00:26:33.340 --> 00:26:36.960
powerful buyers in automobile
manufacturers.

00:26:36.960 --> 00:26:39.818
You want to avoid situations
like that.

00:26:39.818 --> 00:26:43.779
You also want to be able to
control your suppliers so they

00:26:43.779 --> 00:26:47.880
can't see you making profits and
then demand their share.

00:26:47.880 --> 00:26:51.430
Now just think for a second.
 

00:26:51.430 --> 00:26:54.997
How do the Porter Forces align
with the conditions that I

00:26:54.997 --> 00:26:58.756
sketched five minutes ago for
the operation of the invisible

00:26:58.756 --> 00:26:59.328
hand?
 

00:26:59.328 --> 00:27:03.644
In the back,
you've got to be really loud

00:27:03.644 --> 00:27:06.730
because the--
Student:  They're the

00:27:06.730 --> 00:27:07.509
exact opposite.
 

00:27:07.509 --> 00:27:10.730
Prof: They are
essentially the exact opposite.

00:27:10.730 --> 00:27:16.265
The name in business speak for
operating under the control of

00:27:16.265 --> 00:27:20.970
the invisible hand is
"commodity hell."

00:27:20.970 --> 00:27:26.582
Commodity hell being that
you're producing something which

00:27:26.582 --> 00:27:30.618
thousands of other people can
produce,

00:27:30.618 --> 00:27:33.509
and they can produce it as
cheaply and as well as you can,

00:27:33.509 --> 00:27:39.170
and so the available pricing
strategies to you are--

00:27:39.170 --> 00:27:41.118
none of them involve high
profits.

00:27:41.118 --> 00:27:47.730
One of the fundamental axioms
of business management--

00:27:47.730 --> 00:27:49.950
and I'm not making a moral
condemnation,

00:27:49.950 --> 00:27:53.134
I'm just making an observation
that there is a strong tension

00:27:53.134 --> 00:27:57.861
here--
that the pursuit of actual--the

00:27:57.861 --> 00:28:03.690
actual submission to the
invisible hand--

00:28:03.690 --> 00:28:10.250
is contrary to the very basis
of corporate strategy.

00:28:10.250 --> 00:28:18.306
Jim, talk a little from your
experience about the intelligent

00:28:18.306 --> 00:28:25.423
use of the Porter Forces by
management strategists--or

00:28:25.423 --> 00:28:27.838
unintelligent.
 

00:28:27.838 --> 00:28:30.660
Jim Alexander:
 Well from the latter--

00:28:30.660 --> 00:28:34.402
but basically no one ever wants
to get into an Adam Smith type

00:28:34.402 --> 00:28:36.291
of market,
and if you're in it,

00:28:36.291 --> 00:28:37.329
you get out of it.
 

00:28:37.329 --> 00:28:40.259
Because there's--it's ruinous.
 

00:28:40.259 --> 00:28:49.131
And the only way you can affect
change in that type of market is

00:28:49.131 --> 00:28:56.154
to do what Adam Smith suggested,
and that is make some sort of

00:28:56.154 --> 00:29:01.290
national security argument why--
in fact, while Smith's views

00:29:01.290 --> 00:29:04.828
are very well and fine in
general,

00:29:04.828 --> 00:29:08.220
you need, and the country more
especially needs,

00:29:08.220 --> 00:29:14.170
to have defense against foreign
imports or ruinous competition.

00:29:14.170 --> 00:29:16.916
I think the sugar producers
were able to pull that off

00:29:16.916 --> 00:29:19.923
pretty neatly and can make a
national security argument for

00:29:19.923 --> 00:29:24.478
it for sugar quotas,
but you never tolerate an Adam

00:29:24.478 --> 00:29:27.519
Smith level of competition.
 

00:29:27.519 --> 00:29:30.608
Prof: Okay,
and if you look at--

00:29:30.608 --> 00:29:34.150
I ordered Thank You For
Smoking,

00:29:34.150 --> 00:29:37.509
Christopher Buckley's book,
as an option for this course,

00:29:37.509 --> 00:29:40.549
but I'm told all of you have
seen the movie,

00:29:40.549 --> 00:29:42.170
which I haven't.
 

00:29:42.170 --> 00:29:44.480
Is the movie any good?
 

00:29:44.480 --> 00:29:45.828
Student:  Yes.
 

00:29:45.828 --> 00:29:47.336
Prof: Okay,
you should all look at the

00:29:47.336 --> 00:29:47.608
movie.
 

00:29:47.608 --> 00:29:53.269
And the book is all about the
way corporations,

00:29:53.269 --> 00:29:56.200
including those which make,
in this case,

00:29:56.200 --> 00:29:58.951
cigarettes, booze,
and firearms,

00:29:58.951 --> 00:30:03.461
but mostly cigarettes,
have elaborate representation

00:30:03.461 --> 00:30:08.440
in Washington and promote their
own interests through the law.

00:30:08.440 --> 00:30:09.848
It's not a big surprise.
 

00:30:09.848 --> 00:30:17.172
But the tension between the
idealized theory of the market

00:30:17.172 --> 00:30:22.440
and that practice is a very
strong one.

00:30:22.440 --> 00:30:25.070
Incidentally,
Smith was very critical of the

00:30:25.070 --> 00:30:28.990
corporations,
which existed in his time,

00:30:28.990 --> 00:30:35.323
and he was critical of them for
partly the reason we just

00:30:35.323 --> 00:30:41.883
articulated: That they can
control pricing and impose their

00:30:41.883 --> 00:30:45.048
product by that method.
 

00:30:45.048 --> 00:30:48.531
But more, Smith thought,
that the people running the

00:30:48.531 --> 00:30:51.536
corporations,
which existed at that time were

00:30:51.536 --> 00:30:53.380
thoroughly incompetent.
 

00:30:53.380 --> 00:30:56.577
And that's, of course,
because the Yale School of

00:30:56.577 --> 00:30:59.108
Management had not yet been
founded.

00:30:59.108 --> 00:31:03.637
In actual fact there is a
fundamental problem about

00:31:03.637 --> 00:31:07.532
corporations and their
management called the

00:31:07.532 --> 00:31:10.160
principal-agency problem.
 

00:31:10.160 --> 00:31:16.078
The gist of that problem is
that managers,

00:31:16.078 --> 00:31:21.703
left to their own devices,
will tend to take a company

00:31:21.703 --> 00:31:24.443
where--
in a direction which is best

00:31:24.443 --> 00:31:28.204
for them individually and not
necessarily for the broad body

00:31:28.204 --> 00:31:32.692
of shareholders,
and so the control over that

00:31:32.692 --> 00:31:38.888
tendency gets to be one of the
major dramatic themes in

00:31:38.888 --> 00:31:40.838
business life.
 

00:31:40.838 --> 00:31:46.365
Jim you've been near some
management, which had rent

00:31:46.365 --> 00:31:48.640
seeking tendencies.
 

00:31:48.640 --> 00:31:51.596
Jim Alexander:
 Well, let me come back to

00:31:51.596 --> 00:31:56.046
something else,
and that is that at least one

00:31:56.046 --> 00:32:02.450
of the sections Smith has
revolves around the butcher,

00:32:02.450 --> 00:32:07.098
the brewer, and the baker,
and how it's much more reliable

00:32:07.098 --> 00:32:11.750
to rely on their self interest
than their benevolence,

00:32:11.750 --> 00:32:14.358
which is true.
 

00:32:14.358 --> 00:32:17.727
There is--I think there is an
embedded assumption which he

00:32:17.727 --> 00:32:20.490
doesn't go into,
and that is:

00:32:20.490 --> 00:32:26.575
he cites examples of what are--
at least at the time,

00:32:26.575 --> 00:32:31.125
where a single proprietor sort
of business is marketing a

00:32:31.125 --> 00:32:35.836
product which was directly
consumed by individuals who knew

00:32:35.836 --> 00:32:39.950
the proprietors well,
and understood what good meat

00:32:39.950 --> 00:32:42.068
was from meat that wasn't good.
 

00:32:42.068 --> 00:32:50.828
And that also is increasingly
irrelevant since his time,

00:32:50.828 --> 00:32:53.930
because one of the most
important things,

00:32:53.930 --> 00:32:57.241
I thought, in one of your
slides, was that there be

00:32:57.241 --> 00:32:58.700
perfect information.
 

00:32:58.700 --> 00:33:01.853
And on top of that,
an embedded assumption there is

00:33:01.853 --> 00:33:04.942
that there has to be perfect
information perfectly

00:33:04.942 --> 00:33:05.890
understood.
 

00:33:05.890 --> 00:33:07.660
Prof: Absolutely.
 

00:33:07.660 --> 00:33:09.608
Jim Alexander:
 In fact one of the--

00:33:09.608 --> 00:33:13.795
and having come from finance,
it's sort of the highest form

00:33:13.795 --> 00:33:17.762
of art is to have information
which in retrospect can be

00:33:17.762 --> 00:33:21.698
defended as reliable,
but prospectively is virtually

00:33:21.698 --> 00:33:22.588
meaningless.
 

00:33:22.588 --> 00:33:27.226
One of the ways we can--that it
really becomes very important in

00:33:27.226 --> 00:33:29.932
practice,
forget about Smithian ideals,

00:33:29.932 --> 00:33:33.328
is to make sure that you have
colorable information,

00:33:33.328 --> 00:33:36.855
colorable voluntary
transactions,

00:33:36.855 --> 00:33:41.233
but in fact,
they are, practically speaking,

00:33:41.233 --> 00:33:44.426
not voluntary,
and, practically speaking,

00:33:44.426 --> 00:33:45.390
not informed.
 

00:33:45.390 --> 00:33:49.670
On top of that you start having
principal-agent issues.

00:33:49.670 --> 00:33:52.720
Let's take the butcher,
for example,

00:33:52.720 --> 00:33:57.368
one butcher in a little village
deals with people he knows,

00:33:57.368 --> 00:34:00.528
so there's social constraints,
and there's also--

00:34:00.528 --> 00:34:02.170
it's fairly easy if it's one
butcher,

00:34:02.170 --> 00:34:06.460
to trace any illnesses that
result.

00:34:06.460 --> 00:34:10.253
And he has a relatively
unmarketable asset,

00:34:10.253 --> 00:34:14.949
which is his interest in his
private butcher shop;

00:34:14.949 --> 00:34:18.744
very hard to sell,
so he must count on long term

00:34:18.744 --> 00:34:23.469
profit maximization;
not short term, but long term.

00:34:23.469 --> 00:34:28.168
Now let's imagine that you had
a--I don't think (inaudible)

00:34:28.168 --> 00:34:32.949
processer is public at this
point but let's imagine that you

00:34:32.949 --> 00:34:37.650
had a butcher business which was
owned by the public,

00:34:37.650 --> 00:34:39.539
controlled by a small group of
managers.

00:34:39.539 --> 00:34:43.333
And furthermore let's assume,
and it's actually a pretty good

00:34:43.333 --> 00:34:45.726
assumption,
that you had a group of

00:34:45.726 --> 00:34:49.525
semi-knowledgeable mutual fund
managers who rewarded people

00:34:49.525 --> 00:34:53.389
with huge gains in their share
value if they were able,

00:34:53.389 --> 00:34:57.871
reliably, to hit their
quarterly earnings estimate and

00:34:57.871 --> 00:35:00.275
punish them,
of course, if anything went

00:35:00.275 --> 00:35:00.570
wrong.
 

00:35:00.570 --> 00:35:04.061
Under those circumstances,
assuming that the investing

00:35:04.061 --> 00:35:08.280
public really didn't understand
the dynamics of the business,

00:35:08.280 --> 00:35:14.139
and assuming that you could
make satisfactory short term

00:35:14.139 --> 00:35:17.344
goals,
maybe making 100 times the

00:35:17.344 --> 00:35:22.349
average income of the typical
worker every couple weeks,

00:35:22.349 --> 00:35:27.268
then you would be incentivized,
unless you were very risk

00:35:27.268 --> 00:35:29.432
adverse to,
for example,

00:35:29.432 --> 00:35:34.019
being able to buy tainted meat
and then be able to make some

00:35:34.019 --> 00:35:36.534
extra pennies,
beat your numbers,

00:35:36.534 --> 00:35:38.639
get a big upgrade in your
stock,

00:35:38.639 --> 00:35:41.219
if you have a lot of options
you have a very highly leveraged

00:35:41.219 --> 00:35:43.853
wealth situation,
then make enough money in the

00:35:43.853 --> 00:35:46.889
short term,
where you could live--maybe buy

00:35:46.889 --> 00:35:51.155
a small country or live with
gravy for the rest of your life

00:35:51.155 --> 00:35:54.552
on a basis which was
sufficiently confusing that

00:35:54.552 --> 00:35:57.300
you're unlikely to be
prosecuted.

00:35:57.300 --> 00:35:59.940
That's my experience as to how
it works.

00:35:59.940 --> 00:36:04.456
I realize that it's a small
sliver and it is oriented toward

00:36:04.456 --> 00:36:06.871
finance,
which is the worst part of

00:36:06.871 --> 00:36:09.889
American business,
but that's in fact how I've

00:36:09.889 --> 00:36:10.829
seen it work.
 

00:36:10.829 --> 00:36:13.429
No theories,
it's just how it works,

00:36:13.429 --> 00:36:16.766
so people believe,
and yet the same people who

00:36:16.766 --> 00:36:21.289
would do this would spout and
believe every bit of it the same

00:36:21.289 --> 00:36:25.960
type of Smithian idealism you
see here: the invisible hand.

00:36:25.960 --> 00:36:28.643
My experience is that the
invisible hand typically is

00:36:28.643 --> 00:36:31.070
picking someone's pocket,
not creating value.

00:36:31.070 --> 00:36:36.143
And in fact,
the last--I remember talking to

00:36:36.143 --> 00:36:43.103
the senior Republic staffer at
The House Energy and Commerce

00:36:43.103 --> 00:36:47.273
Committee and making--
Prof: Jim is,

00:36:47.273 --> 00:36:49.440
by the way, I believe you are a
Republican.

00:36:49.440 --> 00:36:50.989
Jim Alexander:
 Used to be.

00:36:50.989 --> 00:36:52.190
Prof: Okay.
 

00:36:52.190 --> 00:36:53.349
Jim Alexander:
 Used to be;

00:36:53.349 --> 00:36:55.539
this is kind of why I used to
be.

00:36:55.539 --> 00:36:58.664
I'm up talking to the lead
Republican staffer at The House

00:36:58.664 --> 00:37:01.789
Energy and Commerce Committee
and saying at one point that

00:37:01.789 --> 00:37:04.530
capitalism justifies itself by
creating real,

00:37:04.530 --> 00:37:05.949
not illusory, value.
 

00:37:05.949 --> 00:37:08.173
To which he replied,
"Well you're nothing but a

00:37:08.173 --> 00:37:08.960
communist."
 

00:37:08.960 --> 00:37:13.570
That, in fact, is the problem.
 

00:37:13.570 --> 00:37:17.849
Under Smithian assumptions
about long-term honesty,

00:37:17.849 --> 00:37:21.445
long-term interests in real
value creation,

00:37:21.445 --> 00:37:23.500
it worked perfectly.
 

00:37:23.500 --> 00:37:27.244
It's just that when those
assumptions start to erode,

00:37:27.244 --> 00:37:29.260
it turns into a nightmare.
 

00:37:29.260 --> 00:37:32.139
Prof: Okay terrific.
 

00:37:32.139 --> 00:37:34.804
Georgios, I'm going to call on
you in a moment for a one

00:37:34.804 --> 00:37:35.579
sentence read.
 

00:37:35.579 --> 00:37:39.079
Here's the proposition that we
now want to look at.

00:37:39.079 --> 00:37:44.510
Smith--here's an apparent but
not real paradox.

00:37:44.510 --> 00:37:50.190
Adam Smith says self-interest
is the main motive for what

00:37:50.190 --> 00:37:52.320
people actually do.
 

00:37:52.320 --> 00:37:57.050
And yet, he led a life,
which didn't begin to maximize

00:37:57.050 --> 00:37:59.639
his own material interests.
 

00:37:59.639 --> 00:38:04.449
He lived modestly,
he worked diligently,

00:38:04.449 --> 00:38:13.032
and he never became a wealthy
man, so if he believed it for

00:38:13.032 --> 00:38:16.585
mankind,
how come he didn't practice it

00:38:16.585 --> 00:38:17.420
for himself?
 

00:38:17.420 --> 00:38:21.313
Well, Richard--
Student:  I just wanted

00:38:21.313 --> 00:38:24.579
to add I think it's probably the
way you define self-interest.

00:38:24.579 --> 00:38:27.659
Self-interest to one person may
not be the same to another,

00:38:27.659 --> 00:38:31.889
so while you just associate it
with wealth and material goods,

00:38:31.889 --> 00:38:34.070
to someone else it's not
necessarily someone else's

00:38:34.070 --> 00:38:35.380
definition of self interest.
 

00:38:35.380 --> 00:38:37.150
Prof: Fair enough,
that's a good point.

00:38:37.150 --> 00:38:40.659
The other side of it is that
Wealth of Nations was

00:38:40.659 --> 00:38:43.666
Smith's second main book,
and it wasn't the book,

00:38:43.666 --> 00:38:46.550
which made him famous in his
own lifetime.

00:38:46.550 --> 00:38:49.231
The Theory of Moral
Sentiments is the book,

00:38:49.231 --> 00:38:51.639
which made him famous in his
own lifetime.

00:38:51.639 --> 00:38:54.960
And Georgios,
will you read us,

00:38:54.960 --> 00:39:01.378
please, in good strong voice,
the first sentence of Smith's

00:39:01.378 --> 00:39:03.039
first book?
 

00:39:03.039 --> 00:39:14.179
Thanks very much Leslie.
 

00:39:14.179 --> 00:39:16.367
Student:  "How
selfish, so ever,

00:39:16.367 --> 00:39:18.605
man may be supposed,
there are evidently some

00:39:18.605 --> 00:39:21.657
principles in his nature which
interest him in the fortune of

00:39:21.657 --> 00:39:24.512
others,
and render their happiness

00:39:24.512 --> 00:39:27.362
necessary to him,
though he derives nothing from

00:39:27.362 --> 00:39:29.199
it except the pleasure of seeing
it."

00:39:29.199 --> 00:39:32.130
Prof: Okay,
now read it one more time.

00:39:32.130 --> 00:39:33.909
Student:  "How
selfish,

00:39:33.909 --> 00:39:37.585
so ever, man may be supposed,
there are evidently some

00:39:37.585 --> 00:39:41.746
principles in his nature which
interest him in the fortune of

00:39:41.746 --> 00:39:44.231
others,
and render their happiness

00:39:44.231 --> 00:39:47.349
necessary to him,
though he derives nothing from

00:39:47.349 --> 00:39:50.090
it except the pleasure of seeing
it."

00:39:50.090 --> 00:39:54.179
Prof: Okay,
so Smith actually believed that

00:39:54.179 --> 00:39:58.518
we were a complicated mix,
and I think he's right.

00:39:58.518 --> 00:40:02.963
He believed that there is a
pro-social element in almost

00:40:02.963 --> 00:40:04.579
every human being.
 

00:40:04.579 --> 00:40:10.059
There is an innate sympathy for
others, which almost everyone

00:40:10.059 --> 00:40:15.266
has, and at the same time,
a tendency to feather one's own

00:40:15.266 --> 00:40:16.090
nest.
 

00:40:16.090 --> 00:40:20.730
Now I don't know anyone who is
just one of those two things.

00:40:20.730 --> 00:40:25.380
I don't know anyone who is a
pure egotist.

00:40:25.380 --> 00:40:27.719
Jim Alexander:  Me.
 

00:40:27.719 --> 00:40:29.440
Prof: You do?
 

00:40:29.440 --> 00:40:36.427
My goodness;
not even generous to his aged

00:40:36.427 --> 00:40:39.385
mother or--
Jim Alexander:

00:40:39.385 --> 00:40:40.579
 What's she done for him?
 

00:40:40.579 --> 00:40:44.914
Prof: Okay,
well there may be some but

00:40:44.914 --> 00:40:47.969
there aren't a hell of a lot.
 

00:40:47.969 --> 00:40:51.940
Smith--this is characteristic
of Smith--Smith is not a

00:40:51.940 --> 00:40:52.840
dogmatist.
 

00:40:52.840 --> 00:41:00.467
Smith is a careful observer who
draws as much from the evidence

00:41:00.467 --> 00:41:02.190
as is there.
 

00:41:02.190 --> 00:41:07.971
Now this is a map which links
Smith forward to the next

00:41:07.971 --> 00:41:14.099
historical period,
namely the period when world

00:41:14.099 --> 00:41:18.159
trade got serious,
and the period,

00:41:18.159 --> 00:41:21.768
which we will discuss in
Monday's class,

00:41:21.768 --> 00:41:24.467
when Marx and Engels were
writing The Communist

00:41:24.467 --> 00:41:25.349
Manifesto.
 

00:41:25.349 --> 00:41:30.650
The picture on the board is the
world railroad grid,

00:41:30.650 --> 00:41:36.097
and if you think about Smith's
story about how wealth depends

00:41:36.097 --> 00:41:40.353
on the division of labor,
it works only where you have a

00:41:40.353 --> 00:41:43.389
large market,
and he makes that point at

00:41:43.389 --> 00:41:44.059
length.
 

00:41:44.059 --> 00:41:47.503
In the period,
which begins in the middle

00:41:47.503 --> 00:41:50.739
1800s,
it really begins about 1840,

00:41:50.739 --> 00:41:55.574
in that period really large
markets became accessible to

00:41:55.574 --> 00:42:01.199
everyone located in the dense
part of the world railway grid.

00:42:01.199 --> 00:42:06.726
And toward the end of the
semester, we'll be dealing with

00:42:06.726 --> 00:42:11.563
the problem of economic
development in places like

00:42:11.563 --> 00:42:12.550
these.
 

00:42:12.550 --> 00:42:18.144
If you look at the way the
railroads developed there,

00:42:18.144 --> 00:42:24.170
they all developed to reach
ocean ports for the export of

00:42:24.170 --> 00:42:27.400
products to world markets.
 

00:42:27.400 --> 00:42:31.989
The density of connection
required for the internal

00:42:31.989 --> 00:42:37.130
development of large markets was
by and large missing.

00:42:37.130 --> 00:42:44.481
Okay, now--I think I'll just
finish with Adam Smith's story

00:42:44.481 --> 00:42:50.186
about the pin making,
and what happened in the

00:42:50.186 --> 00:42:52.849
pin-making story.
 

00:42:52.849 --> 00:42:56.507
I actually didn't have you read
this because it's something

00:42:56.507 --> 00:43:00.420
everybody--I think everybody
learns this one in high school.

00:43:00.420 --> 00:43:05.413
The division of labor for Smith
is illustrated by a group of

00:43:05.413 --> 00:43:07.360
artisans making pins.
 

00:43:07.360 --> 00:43:14.150
One person gets really good at
drawing the wire out straight,

00:43:14.150 --> 00:43:17.630
another person at hammering a
head onto the wire,

00:43:17.630 --> 00:43:20.210
another person at making the
point sharp,

00:43:20.210 --> 00:43:22.360
another person at polishing the
shaft.

00:43:22.360 --> 00:43:27.440
And by division of labor and
development of expertise,

00:43:27.440 --> 00:43:31.173
they can produce more pins of
higher quality than a single

00:43:31.173 --> 00:43:34.711
artisan doing each of those
operations by himself could

00:43:34.711 --> 00:43:36.219
possibly have done.
 

00:43:36.219 --> 00:43:39.849
It's a good illustration.
 

00:43:39.849 --> 00:43:44.925
And if you think about all the
professions and occupations in

00:43:44.925 --> 00:43:48.635
an economy,
that kind of profiting--that

00:43:48.635 --> 00:43:52.693
way of profiting from
specialized expertise is

00:43:52.693 --> 00:43:56.030
foundational to market
societies,

00:43:56.030 --> 00:43:58.239
foundational to their wealth.
 

00:43:58.239 --> 00:44:02.708
Now the actual fate of the pin
machine is interesting,

00:44:02.708 --> 00:44:05.070
and personal to my family.
 

00:44:05.070 --> 00:44:11.519
It turns out that in 1831,
a New York physician named John

00:44:11.519 --> 00:44:17.518
Ireland Howe began to tinker
with the idea of making a

00:44:17.518 --> 00:44:24.309
machine where wire went in one
end and polished pins came out

00:44:24.309 --> 00:44:28.268
the other in their thousands.
 

00:44:28.268 --> 00:44:33.219
By 1851 he perfected what was
called the Howe Pin Machine.

00:44:33.219 --> 00:44:37.079
There's a room in the
Smithsonian to this day where a

00:44:37.079 --> 00:44:41.309
Howe Pin Machine sits and a
movie of its operation goes on

00:44:41.309 --> 00:44:42.349
behind it.
 

00:44:42.349 --> 00:44:44.759
Well John Ireland Howe,
I won't brag again in this

00:44:44.759 --> 00:44:47.268
semester,
was my five over great

00:44:47.268 --> 00:44:50.500
grandfather,
and the family began pissing

00:44:50.500 --> 00:44:54.414
away the money right away,
and completed the task just in

00:44:54.414 --> 00:44:55.619
time for my birth.
 

